Q: Duplicate custom Order Action in WooCommerce A: <p>To add another different action to your code, you need to edit your first function, adding the desired action like:</p>
<pre class="lang-php prettyprint-override"><code>function custom_status_action( $actions ) {
    unset($actions['send_osm_email_ready-to-collect']);

    $actions['ns_fba_send_to_fulfillment'] = __( 'Send Ready to Collect custom email', 'woocommerce' );
    // Here below you add your custom action
    $actions['ns_fba_send_collected']      = __( 'Send Order has been collected custom email', 'woocommerce' );

    return $actions;
}
add_action( 'woocommerce_order_actions', 'custom_status_action', 999 );
</code></pre>
<p>Now you need an additional hooked function to be triggered when you call your related additional custom action. Here the hook used is a composite hook made of &quot;woocommerce_order_action_&quot; + <em>the action slug</em> defined in your first function.</p>
<p>First we can simplify (or optimize) your current 2nd function code, using <code>array_key_exists()</code> php function instead of using a <code>foreach</code> loop:</p>
<pre><code>function ns_fba_send_to_fulfillment_process( $order ) {
    $email_id     = 'wc_order_status_email_6181';
    $order_status = 'wc-ready';

    $wc_emails    = WC()-&gt;mailer()-&gt;get_emails();

    if ( $wc_emails &amp;&amp; array_key_exists($email_id, $wc_emails) ) {
        $wc_emails[$email_id]-&gt;trigger( $order-&gt;get_id() ); // Send the email notification

        $order-&gt;update_status( $order_status ); // Update order status ans save
    }
}
add_action( 'woocommerce_order_action_ns_fba_send_to_fulfillment', 'ns_fba_send_to_fulfillment_process' );
</code></pre>
<p>Also as the <code>save</code> method is already included in the <code>WC_Order update_status()</code>, we don't need it.</p>
<p>Now we can add that additional hooked function to be triggered when you call your related additional custom action, based on the code from the function above, that send the related email notification and change the order status.</p>
<pre><code>function ns_fba_send_collected_process( $order ) {
    $email_id     = 'wc_order_status_email_xxxx'; // &lt;= Define the correct Email ID
    $order_status = 'wc-new-status'; // &lt;= Define the desired order status to update

    $wc_emails    = WC()-&gt;mailer()-&gt;get_emails();

    if ( $wc_emails &amp;&amp; array_key_exists($email_id, $wc_emails) ) {
        $wc_emails[$email_id]-&gt;trigger( $order-&gt;get_id() ); // Send the email notification

        $order-&gt;update_status( $order_status ); // Update order status ans save
    }
}
add_action( 'woocommerce_order_action_ns_fba_send_collected', 'ns_fba_send_collected_process' );
</code></pre>
<p>In the code above you need to define the correct <strong>email ID</strong> and <strong>order status</strong> corresponding to your new additional custom action.</p>
<p>Related: <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/77512613/use-woocommerce-wc-order-object-with-wp-schedule-event/77513008#77513008">Use WooCommerce WC_Order object with wp_schedule_event</a></p>

Q: Return an unexported type from a function A: <p>While it mostly makes sense to export types which you give to caller for easier references, it can be legit not to do so. Imagine designing a domain driven application and having roots, would you always export root types?</p>
<p>Another example where this could be interesting would be a library code which makes the effort to not expose types which are not needed to be part of contracts - makes refactoring without breaking code easier.</p>
<p>Limitations people face are often related to exported properties on structs, which is the same problem if access happens over an interface - this is something to be aware of.</p>
<p>That said, most of the times you should listen to linter, it is more practical in Go to export types.</p>
<p>To give a simple example on how you can go about unexported types:</p>
<pre class="lang-golang prettyprint-override"><code>package runner

import &quot;fmt&quot;

type hiddenType struct{}

func NewHiddenType() *hiddenType {
        return &amp;hiddenType{}
}

func (h *hiddenType) Run() {
    fmt.Println(&quot;Running&quot;)
}

// in main.go
package main

import &quot;runner&quot;

type runnable interface {
    Run()
}

type DependantStruct struct {
    r runnable
}

func (d *DependantStruct) Do() {
    d.onlyExported.Run()
}

func main() {
    secret := runner.NewHiddenType()
    dep := &amp;DependantStruct{r: secret}
    dep.Do()
}
</code></pre>
